div1.p:
Cross-examined by MR. BRODRICK. Q. When the will was brought to you, was it stated by Whyman that he had made the will? A. It was, and that in the prisoner's presence;
Michael Whyman
's name was to it as an attesting witness - he stated that he made the will for Brandrith.

Q. Did he explain what he meant by things? A. Whether he said sheep I do not know, I imagine he must; I was to go and dress them - he gave me some gamble-hooks, tied in a blue apron; they are to stick in the legs of the sheep to hang them up; I went from there to a gin-shop with him, and he gave me a drop of gin; and from there I went to No. 92, Edgware-road - he did not go with me, I understood him that he was going to Smithfield - he told me to go on to Mr. Johnson's, and there was somebody there to help me kill these things; I parted from him when he told me he was going to Smithfield, and got to Johnson's about half-past seven o'clock - I was very lame, and not able to walk fast; when I got near Johnson's I saw the door was open, and some sheep in the road at a distance - I suppose about thirty, but did not count them; I saw two men at a distance with the sheep; I went into Johnson's shop - there was no person in the shop then; I called Johnson - the sheep were driven into the shop; I assisted to drive them in - the other two men, Mr. Johnson, and other people who were passing, also assisted; they might be ten minutes or a quarter of an hour bringing the sheep in; I could not swear to the two other men who were with the sheep - I never saw them before to my knowledge - I never saw the other prisoners to my knowledge till they were at Hatton-garden - I cannot swear at all to them; I never saw them before - if they are the men, they were dressed different at the office, and I considered that one was taller and the other shorter than the prisoners - to the best of my knowledge they were; I then went to get somebody to help me kill these sheep; I returned about half-past ten or a quarter to eleven o'clock;
Henry Wincott
and a man called Poultice, were the men who returned with me to assist in killing them - when I returned with them I saw Newitt forty or fifty yards on this side Johnson's house; I told him there was nobody there to help me, and I had been to fetch these two men; he asked if we would have some gin, to the best of my knowledge; he said he had heard in Holborn that there was nobody to help - he told us to go and get to work, to get some sheep dead; the men who was with me went and stuck the sheep, and I was stripping ready to dress them - I went in with them; Newitt came in a little time, and brought some ale into the yard in a pot while we were engaged with the sheep - I did not count them and cannot say how many were killed - we killed the whole in the yard, which was about thirty; I did not take notice what breed they were: there was no black one; there was a kind of brown one.
